# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carlos-manuel-zecca
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The **1957 Little League World Series** took place during August 21 through 23 in Williamsport, Pennsylvania.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Industrial Little League of Monterrey, Nuevo León, Mexico, defeated Northern La Mesa Little League of La Mesa, California, in the championship game of the 11th Little League World Series (LLWS). Ángel Macías threw the first and, to date, only perfect game in an LLWS championship.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] This was the first LLWS to invite teams from qualifying regions: North, South, East, and West.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Monterrey, representing the South region, became the first team from outside the United States or Canada to participate in a LLWS, and the first non-U.S. team to win a championship.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In 1956, Monterrey was granted a Little League license.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] They assembled a four-team "Industrial Little League" consisting of teams from different factories, the Botelleros, Mineros, Tubitos, and Incas.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Many of the kids came from low-income families and even worked in the factories themselves.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Before the teams could play, they had to clear the field of rocks and broken glass.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] They even had to use homemade gloves and equipment.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In 1957, the league had a tryout for a Little League team that would represent the city.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The coach, Cesar Faz, recruited the kids.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He became known as a great baseball coach and was considered one of the best at motivating a youth baseball team.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In July, after playing two exhibition games in Mexico, the Monterrey team's historic run to the Little League World Series began.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team first took a bus to Reynosa, Mexico.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] From there, they crossed the Mexico–United States border, walking across a bridge over the Rio Grande.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team then continued on to a hotel in McAllen, Texas.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In McAllen, they played a U.S. subregional tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team won their first game against a team from Mexico City, 9–2.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] They went on to defeat the McAllen All Stars, the Mission All Stars, the Weslaco All Stars, and the Western Brownsville All Stars to advance to a regional tournament in Corpus Christi.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] While there, they beat another team from Mexico City and then beat the Houston All Stars.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team then travelled to Fort Worth to play in the Texas State Tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Up until that point, they had beat every team by at least five runs.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] However, in the state semifinals, they needed extra innings to beat another Houston All Star team, 6–4.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] After they survived that game, they defeated the Waco All Stars, 11–2, to advance to the tournament of Little League's South Region.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team got on a plane and flew to Louisville, Kentucky, for the South Region tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Their first game was against Biloxi, Mississippi.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The next game, for the South Region championship, was against Owensboro, Kentucky.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The Monterrey team was now headed to the Little League World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team loaded up on to a bus and headed 700 miles (1,100 km) northwest to Williamsport, Pennsylvania.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] During all this, the players' visas expired.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The U.S. ambassador to Mexico had to intervene to keep them legally in the country.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team was young, in a foreign country, and away from their families—only one of the players had ever left Monterrey before.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team also didn't have a lot of money for food, only being able to eat twice a day.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] It was only through the kindness of strangers and a few new friends who fed them, offered them meals at restaurants, and gave them some money after a win, that they were able to keep going.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] On the field, no team from outside the U.S. had ever won a game at the Little League World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Two Canadian teams had previously made it to Williamsport, but each had lost the only game they played.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] When they arrived in Williamsport, Little League officials gave them new uniforms that said "South" across the chest.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] However, the uniforms did not fit because the Monterrey players were so much smaller than players on the other teams, as the boys from Monterrey averaged 4 feet 11 inches (1.50 m) and 92 pounds (42 kg), while the other teams' players averaged 5 feet 4 inches (1.63 m) and 127 pounds (58 kg).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Unfazed, they beat Bridgeport, Connecticut, 2–1, to reach the championship game.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] They were set to face La Mesa, California, who had easily beaten Escanaba, Michigan.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Many people believed that the boys from Monterrey had little chance to win.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Even some of the Monterrey players were questioning what would happen to them the next day.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The coach, Cesar Faz, decided to name Ángel Macías as the starting pitcher for the championship game.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] What he did that day led him to become known as "The Little Big Man".
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He stood 5 feet (1.5 m) tall and weighed 88 pounds (40 kg).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] However, he decided to only throw with his right hand in this game.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In the championship game, the first batter, Lew Riley of La Mesa, hit the first pitch of the game on a hard line drive down the first base line; it was foul by an inch.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] That was the closest La Mesa came to a hit all afternoon.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] In front of 10,000 people in Williamsport, and others listening via radio in Monterrey, Macías proceeded to be perfect—he did not allow a batter to get on a base.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He struck out 11 out of the 18 batters he faced, and no ball left the infield.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] With two outs in the 6th (final) inning, La Mesa's Bryon Haggard stepped into the box.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Macías quickly fell behind in the count, 3–0.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He proceeded to battle back and threw two strikes to make it a full count.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Macías then wound up and threw a curveball that made Haggard swing and miss.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Macías had thrown a perfect game in a Little League World Series championship game, the first player to do so.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team from Monterrey became the first team from outside the United States to win the Little League World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The next morning, the story was getting national and international coverage and attention.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Newspapers and news stations ran stories about the team from Monterrey.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Having won the Little League World Series, the team's first thought was to go home.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] However, it would be almost a month until the team returned to Monterrey.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] They began their victory tour by traveling by bus to New York City.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] While they were there, the Brooklyn Dodgers invited them to be their guest at Ebbets Field.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team then went shopping at Macy's Department Store and were each given $40 to spend.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] After leaving New York, the team headed to Washington D.C.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] While they were there, they met with President Dwight D.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Eisenhower and Vice President Richard Nixon.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] There, they met with Mexican President Ruiz Cortinez and attended celebrations.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team then flew from Mexico City to their hometown of Monterrey.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] When they arrived, they were met with tens of thousands of people in the streets.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] It started at the airport and stretched to the Government Palace.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] During the parade, people were trying to take parts of their uniforms, hats, belts, cleats as memorabilia and souvenirs.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] After the parade, the Mexican government awarded all 14 members of the team a scholarship for both high school and college education.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] However, only two of them ever actually went to college.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] According to a few of the players, everywhere they went, people recognized them and wanted autographs.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The team went on to successfully defend their Little League title the following year.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] As the players grew up, they all went their separate ways.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] At age 16, Angel Macías was signed by the American League's new expansion team, the Los Angeles Angels.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He was invited to their spring training in 1961.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He played for a couple of seasons (1962–1963) as an outfielder in Minor League Baseball, advancing as far as the Class A California League.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He also played a total of 12 seasons in Mexico, primarily in the Mexican League with Broncos de Reynosa and Sultanes de Monterrey.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] After his playing career, he ran the Mexican Academy, which is a minor league circuit.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] He was inducted into Little League Hall of Excellence in 2017.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] One of the other players, Jose "Pepe" Maiz, also was inducted in 2005.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] Both Maiz and Macías did a lot for the growth of baseball in Mexico.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] As of 2017, Maiz also ran a construction company and owned the Sultanes de Monterrey.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] There were two movies made about the 1957 historic run of Monterrey Little League: a 1960 Mexican production called *Los Pequeños Gigantes* and a 2009 film called *The Perfect Game*.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] The *Futility Closet* podcast covered the team and their Little League World Series championship in an episode.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1957-little-league-world-series] California's first game was played a day later than planned, due to illness within the team, resulting in the third-place game also being delayed a day.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] The **1961 Amateur World Series** was the 15th edition of the Amateur World Series of international baseball.It was the only one held in Costa Rica, taking place in San Jose from April 7 through April 21, 1961.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] The 1961 tournament was the first Amateur World Series to be held since the 1953 edition, and the first major baseball tournament since the 1957 Global World Series in Detroit.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] It was also the first international tournament to feature a Cuban entry since the Cuban revolution.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Coincidentally, the tournament was ongoing while anti-Castro Cuban exiles, supported by the United States, stormed the Bay of Pigs.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Ten countries participated in the 1961 Amateur World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] They were divided into two qualifying groups; the three teams with the best record in each group moved on to the final round.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] The tryouts for the Cuban national team were held simultaneously to the establishment of INDER and the replacement of professional sports with amateurism in Cuba, including the abolition of the professional Cuban Winter League.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Clemente Carreras was the manager for Cuba; he had previously skippered the national team in the 1952 Amateur World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Venezuela, fresh off a gold medal run at the 1959 Pan American Games were considered the favorites at the tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] The team was mainly composed of players from the Intendencia Naval amateur club, managed by José Manuel Tovar.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] The Netherlands Antilles were piloted by former Cuban Leaguer Agapito Mayor.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] In group play, Panama advanced out of Group A with a 4-0 record, followed by Venezuela (3-1) and the hosts, Costa Rica (2-2).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] In Group B, Cuba (4-0) and Mexico (3-1) qualified for the final round easily.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Cuba defeated the Dutch Antilles 18–0, Nicaragua 16–0, Guatemala 25–0, and Mexico 11–1.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] However, Guatemala, Nicaragua and the Netherlands Antilles all tied with a record of 1-3, playing an extra series to decide who would advance to the final round; Guatemala defeated Nicaragua 6-5 and the Netherlands Antilles 8-1 to qualify for the final.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] In the decisive stage, Cuba again went undefeated, besting Panama (12–3), Guatemala (13–2), Mexico (13–1), Costa Rica (12–2), and Venezuela (9–3).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Mexico and Venezuela took the podium spots, with a record of 4-1 and 3-2 respectively.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Cuba was carried by pitchers Alfredo Street (3-0) and Jose M.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Pineda (2-0); Pineda allowed only one run and one walk in 18 innings of play, striking out 27 batters.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Several Cuban players attracted the attention of major league scouts.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1961-amateur-world-series] Three of them, Bert Campaneris, Tito Fuentes, and José Miguel Pineda, signed major league contracts; Campaneris and Fuentes went on to have long major league careers, while Pineda ultimately chose to remain in Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The **1965 Amateur World Series** was the 16th edition of the Amateur World Series of international baseball.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The tournament was held from February 12 through February 27, 1965 in the Colombian cities of Cartagena and Barranquilla.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The tournament was marked by the absence of defending champions Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The Colombian government, which had broken off diplomatic relations with Cuba following the Cuban Revolution, refused to grant visas to the team of Cuban players.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Colombia and Mexico both finished the regular tournament with a 7-1 record.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] In the tie-breaking playoff series, Colombia defeated Mexico two games to one, to win its second international championship; it had previously won the 1947 Amateur World Series, also held in Colombia.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Though post-revolutionary Cuba had participated in the 1961 Amateur World Series, it was not without controversy as several Cuban players, including Bert Campaneris defected.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] In 1965, the situation was complicated by the fact that Colombia, the host of the series, had severed diplomatic ties with the Castro regime in 1961; the right-wing government of Guillermo León Valencia refused to issue visas to the Cuba national team.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Cuba protested the move, and International Olympic Committee president Avery Brundage attempted to intervene on Cuba's behalf, but he was rebuffed by Carlos Manuel Zecca, president of the International Baseball Federation (FIBA).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Though Houston Astros scout Tony Pacheco expressed interest in forming a "Free Cuba" team composed of Cuban exiles to compete, ultimately no squad representing Cuba appeared in the 1965 tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Pacheco would ultimately pilot the Colombian team.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The tournament was dominated by Colombia, the hosts, and Mexico.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] It saw two notable pitching feats: a perfect game, thrown by Mexico's David Garcia against Guatemala on February 14; and a 19-strikeout game (a tournament record for a single game) thrown by Puerto Rico's Efrain Contreras against the Dutch Antilles on February 22.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] The group stage featured a round robin format to determine the medal winners.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Since Mexico and Colombia tied for first with a 7–1 record, a best-of-three tie-breaker round was played.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1965-amateur-world-series] Calvo (MEX), Ovidio Lara (SLV), Reinaldo Suárez (PAN), S.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The **1969 Amateur World Series** was the 17th edition of the Amateur World Series international baseball tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] It was held, for the first time, in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, from August 15 through August 26, 1969.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The competition marked the first time the United States participated in the Amateur World Series since the 1942 tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Cuba and the US were both 9-0 when they met in the finals, with Cuba winning 2–1.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Gaspar Pérez was the winning pitcher for Cuba and also drove in their first run to tie the game and scored the second, decisive run.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Most of the 20,000 fans who watched the finals were pro-Cuba, reportedly due to lingering resentment from the 1965 US invasion of the Dominican Republic.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The 1969 edition of the Amateur World Series would be a watershed for international competition, as it saw the return of two powerhouses, the United States and Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The United States, which had not participated in the tournament since withdrawing from the 1942 edition, returned after a 27-year absence.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] After their victory in the 1967 Pan American Games in Winnipeg, Canada had spurred renewed interest in international competitions, William P.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] "Dutch" Fehring, president of the rejuvenated United States Baseball Federation (USBF), decided to actively participate in International Baseball Federation (FIBA) competitions.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Cuba returned after being absent for the 1965 tournament in Colombia, which it was unable to attend due to visa issues brought on by the Cold War.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Dominican authorities were active to ensure that political protests did not derail the event, detaining several protesters.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Nevertheless, historians suggest that Dominican President Joaquín Balaguer used the event as propaganda, as a means of legitimizing his rule and positioning the Dominican Republic as an international actor friendly to both the capitalist U.S. and communist Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] Venezuela, which had also not attended in 1965, also made its return.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The tournament, eventually realized in the Dominican Republic, was initially slated to take place in Colombia, which had hosted the 1965 Amateur World Series, in February 1969.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] However, these plans were abruptly cancelled in December 1968 due to a dispute between the Colombian Baseball Federation and the central government.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] On April 30, 1969, it was announced that the tournament had been rescheduled for the Dominican Republic.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/1969-amateur-world-series] The last two encounters between the two sides, at the 1967 Pan American Games in Winnipeg and the 1968 International Amateur Tournament in Mexico City, had seen the U.S. defeat Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/aldo-notari] Notari played 17 seasons as a second baseman for Parma, and was present when the first professional game in Italy was played in 1948.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/aldo-notari] He later went on to act as president of the club, leading it to four Italian League titles and six European Cup championships.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/aldo-notari] Notari succeeded Bruno Beneck as the president of the Italian Baseball Softball Federation (FIBS) in 1985, and became president of the European Amateur Baseball Confederation (CEBA) two years later.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/aldo-notari] After being elected president of the IBAF, Notari sought to increase the level of international tournaments by relaxing the restrictions on professional baseball players, starting with the 1998 Baseball World Cup in Italy.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/aldo-notari] However, he failed to reach an agreement with Major League Baseball (MLB) and their Players Association (MLBPA), and was said to have a particularly acrimonious relationship with MLBPA president Donald Fehr.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The **Baseball World Cup** (**BWC**) was an international baseball tournament for national teams around the world, sanctioned by the International Baseball Federation (IBAF).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] First held in 1938 as the **Amateur World Series** (**AWS**), it was, for most of its history, the highest level of international baseball competition in the world.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Even after it was supplanted in this regard in 2006 by the modern World Baseball Classic (WBC), the Baseball World Cup was still considered by the IBAF to be a major world championship, along with the WBC and the Summer Olympic Games.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Early international baseball competition followed the strict Olympic rules on amateurism, prohibiting "professional" players from leagues such as Major League Baseball and its upper minor league teams.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Because of this, the tournament was dominated by countries with political interest in circumventing amateur rules, such as Cuba, which dissolved its professional baseball league after the Cuban Revolution and given all its top full-time players phantom jobs.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The tournament was eventually opened to professionals, with minor league players competing, though the desire to use top-level, major league players spurred the creation of the World Baseball Classic.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The Baseball World Cup was held 38 times; the final one was in 2011 in Panama.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The first tournament, held in 1938, featured only two teams, but the last tournament included 22 participants; the previous two featured 16 and 18 teams (in 2007 and 2005, respectively).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The World Cup was originally called the Amateur World Series, until the tournament in 1988.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The idea of a baseball competition for national teams was championed by International Baseball Federation (IBF) president Leslie Mann.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] After managing to include baseball as a demonstration sport at the 1936 Berlin Olympics, Mann sought to organize an international tournament in 1937 between the national teams of the United States and Japan; this plan was derailed by the outbreak of the Second Sino-Japanese War that same year.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Instead, Mann wrote to John Moores, president of the British National Baseball Association (the precursor to the modern British Baseball Federation) to organize a tournament between the U.S. and Great Britain teams.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The 1938 "John Moores Cup," as it was originally called, would be retroactively recognized as the first Amateur World Series.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Mann, along with Cuban sports administrator Jaime Mariné, helped turn the Amateur World Series into an annual event in 1939, this time held in Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The first and second tournaments featured only two and three national teams, respectively, but seven participants were invited to the 1940 edition and the pool would only expand from there.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] For much of its early existence, the competition was limited to the nations of Central America and the Caribbean; the United States withdrew early from the 1942 series, and would not return until 1969.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The next edition, in 1970, saw two European national teams (Italy and the Netherlands) participate for the first time; in 1972, Japan became the first Asian country to participate in the global baseball tournament.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Until 1998 the competition was limited to strictly amateur and state-funded players.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] After 1998, professional minor league players competed, but Major League Baseball did not release its players to participate.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] In the months leading up to the high-profile first World Baseball Classic in 2006, many commentators heralded it as a "Baseball World Cup", realizing that a tournament of that description already existing for almost seventy years was not a real World Cup.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] The champions of the first several Amateur World Series tournaments were presented the John Moores Trophy, named in honor of John Moores, a sponsor of the British Baseball Federation and future Everton F.C. executive.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] When Jaime Mariné succeeded Leslie Mann as president of the IBF during the 1940 Amateur World Series, he renamed the trophy the *Copa Presidente Batista*, after Fulgencio Batista, the president of Cuba.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/amateur-world-series] Mariné had participated in the Cuban Revolution of 1933 that brought Batista to power and had organized the dictator's Military Intelligence Service in 1935.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The birth of Baseball Federation of Asia goes back to 1954 when the 2nd Asian Games was held in Manila, Philippines.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The four countries of Korea, Japan, Taiwan and the Philippines organized a committee aiming at establishing the Baseball Federation of Asia and 7 May of the same year witnessed the commencement of BFA.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] American expatriate Charles "Chick" Parsons of the Philippines was elected as the first president of the Baseball Federation of Asia.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The BFA became inactive for eight years following the 1975 Asian Baseball Championship.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] At the sidelines of the FEMBA World Baseball Championship in Tokyo in 1980, the executives of BFA discussed about resuming the activity of the federation.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The Asian Baseball Championship was later resumed in 1983 which was held in Seoul.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The membership of the federation grew as more Asian nations were admitted to the BFA.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/asian-baseball-federation] The total number of BFA members at the present time is 24 and 1 non-member observer State (Vietnam).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] During his tenure as FIBA president, Zecca organized several regional baseball tournaments, including one in 1956 that saw multiple Central American and Caribbean countries participate.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] He served as the president of the Costa Rican Baseball Federation starting in 1960.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Zecca attempted to centralize the organization, inspired by the example set by the Confederation of European Baseball in 1955.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] He sought to organize a youth world championship and promoted the Monterrey team's in their championship-winning 1957 Little League World Series campaign, becoming the first team from outside the United States or Canada to participate.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Zecca also took the first steps in organizing international baseball outside the Americas, promoting the foundation of the Asian Baseball Federation.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] He was a major proponent of including baseball in the Olympic Games, and managed to secure recognition from the International Olympic Committee; baseball was included as a demonstration sport in 1956 and 1964, though FIBA was unsuccessful in making it a medal sport.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] After a long hiatus, he reorganized the Amateur World Series in 1961, which was held in his home country of Costa Rica.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] It was held again in Colombia in 1965 (though with the controversial absence of the Cuba national team, which was denied visas by the Colombian government).
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Zecca secured the return of the United States to the Amateur World Series in 1969; participation of the European nations would follow the next year under his successor, Juan Isa.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Zecca's tenure as FIBA president was controversial, as other Central American federations accused his administration as reflecting his own personal ambition rather than the interest of the game.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Much of the controversy surrounded the participation of communist Cuba in international events, after the Venezuelan government's decision to deny visas to Cuban players scuttled plans for an Amateur World Series there.
[src:carlos-manuel-zecca/carlos-manuel-zecca] Zecca stood for reelection at the FIBA Congress held in the Dominican Republic in 1969, but lost to Isa in an election that returned just one incumbent to the executive committee.
